Korean 1K Vocabulary Deck

Refold Languages

Read this article to get all the details of the deck.

READ THIS!

This deck is meant to be used with the Refold method of language learning. It assumes that you are immersing in Korean media and studying Korean grammar.

This deck just plants the seeds, but immersion is the water that helps those seeds grow.

You should already know how to read Hangul prior to reviewing this deck.

Attribution

Words

The list of words was derived from a corpus of kdramas. See this article for full details.

Sentences

The sentences in this deck were chosen from the compiled corpus of kdramas.

Audio

The audio was custom recorded for this deck by the Boundless graded listener platform.

If you have any copyright concerns, please send us an email at feedback@refold.la.

If you have any questions, ideas, or errors to report, please contact us through our Discord server or send us an email at feedback@refold.la.

fields: 안녕하다 = to be peaceful, to be calm
I have / There is. (lit: it exists)
I'm doing it. / Let's do it.
The subject is unclear here, so a proper English translation is impossible. This word changes thousands of other Korean words into verbs, and is also a verb itself.
Usually occurs in the name of giant conglomerates. E.g. "H.M. Group" or "Cha-myung Group" or in kpop groups with "Boy Group" (보이그룹) and "Girl Group" (걸그룹)

There are two counting systems in Korean. "Pure Korean" and "Sino-Korean". When telling time, the hour is in Pure Korean numbers and minutes and seconds are in Sino-Korean numbers. So 30 is pronounced 삼십 here.
Levels of formality and politeness are built into the Korean language. 반말 is the form used between close friends, or adults speaking to children.
You'll often hear this used as a generic term for 'food'. 밥은 먹었어요? Have you eaten?
선생 = teacher; -님 = suffix for respectful address
Seconds use Sino-Korean numbers, so 10 is pronounced 십 here.
female's older brother or older male friend
male's older brother or older male friend
For example, a fan of a celebrity or idol.
female's older sister or older female friend
male's older sister or older female friend
반갑다 = to be happy to see [something/someone]
When addressing a superior politely and formally, it is common to use both 하세요 and the -습니까? to greet them properly.

This word is a 2-character word that uses the Chinese characters 진 (眞), meaning "true" and 자 (字) which helps words become nouns, and in some situations is pronounced as 짜- to mean "really" or "real". The same pattern of nominalization (noun-ifying) creates words like 남자, 여자, 공짜, 가짜, etc.
좋다 = to be good, to be nice
괜찮다 = to be fine, to be ok
Specifically a manager of an actor, singer, idol, celebrity, etc.
아프다 = to be in pain, to hurt, to be sick
많다 = to be a lot, to be many
A phrase of encouragement, often meaning something along the lines of "good luck" or "do your best".
This comes from the English word "fighting", but Korean doesn't have an 'f' sound. Sometimes you'll also hear it as 파이팅.
Years are counted in Sino-Korean numbers, so 3 is 삼 here.
group blind date, (occasionally used for business meetings as well)

From "meeting". But it specifically refers to when a group of evenly numbered young men and young women get together as an introduction. They'll usually pair up towards the end of the "meeting" and potentially go on dates.
Usually consumed with beer (a.k.a. 맥주), a pairing that is so common that it has its own abbreviation, taking the first syllable of each word: 치맥.
Won are counted in Sino-Korean numbers, so 2000 is pronounced 이천 here.
They'll also use this about the youngest person on a team at work, or in a kpop group.
되다 = to become, to bring into reality, to bring to fruition
This is used in the sense of "No, you musn't!" or "No, don't!"
receive the call; answer the phone
This word combines 소개 "introduction" and 팅 which is short for "meeting". Blind dates in Korean culture are a somewhat more formal matchmaking deal than you'd see in the US.
a thing I use every day
It's nice to meet you, Min-woo Kim.
씨 = polite way of addressing someone who is at the same level as oneself.
Do you have any milk, by any chance?
두다 = to put, to put down
되다 = to become, to bring into reality, to bring to fruition
Often used in situations where we'd say "Stop!" or "Stop right there!"
A false cognate in many cases. A Korean speaker might refer to an appointment or plans that they have as "a schedule", as in "I have a schedule later."
Did you wait a long time?

This is used to mean "first" in the most neutral way. For example, this word can be used to mean "do this first", but it can also be used to yield to someone else. The phrase "After you!" which English speakers use to permit someone else to do something before you, could be said in Korean as "Please go first - 먼저 가세요~"

This word represents the sound of hitting your hand or fingers against a surface - imagine you are pinpointing exactly the place you wish to go on a map - 딱! is the sound of hitting that point. In that way, it is used as an adverb to describe both the idea of precision, and also used to emphasize the severity of an action.
힘들다 = to be hard (as in difficult, burdensome)

This expression can't be translated succinctly into English - it encompasses the idea of being tired, of something being difficult, being exhausting or exhausted, and wraps them all together into one idea.
This is often used to curse at people. Extremely common, and doesn't have a direct English equivalent. It is censored on TV.
what a waste; that's such a shame
아깝다 = to be a shame (as in, disappointing)
it's not over yet; I'm not finished yet
did you buy a birthday present?
Did you send a text message?
This is the answer to "Have you seen X?" if the answer is no.
중 = amid, in the middle of
one's "act" or "state of being under control" - (e.g. get your act together), spirit
I have a request; I have a favor to ask of you.
It's super scary. OR I'm scared.
incessantly, repeatedly, over and over again
필요하다 = to need; 필요 = a need; 하다 = to do
I don't want to hear it.
듣다 = to hear, to listen to

This word is comprised of the Chinese character 第 제 - which is used to make ordinal numbers, and 一 일 which is the Chinese character for 1. In that sense, it can literally mean "first" (you can replace the number 1 with any number to make it an ordinal number) and also be used to make superlatives in Korean, functioning much like "-est" in English.
Please speak. / Go ahead (with your speking). / Please continue (speaking).
Probably comes from poker term "call", but is used as a general way of saying "yeah!", "I'm in"
I'm in a good mood today.
두다 = to put, to put down
Literally: I put it down at home and then came.
will we be able to go back?
Do you want to eat ramen (with me)?
This is used in the exact same way as "Neflix and chill" is in English. The speaker is suggesting to the listener that they retire to the speaker's home after a date.
a women over 40 or who is married. - similar to "Mrs." or "Madame".
please spare me / please save me
I'm a bit busy right now.
당연하다 = to be reasonable, to be natural
년 = offensive word for a girl or woman
사귀다 = to go out with, to date
It's not the least bit scary.
바꾸다 = to change; 비밀번호 = password (비밀 + 번호)
솔직하다 = to be frank, to be honest
쌤 is a shortened version of 선생님
for no good reason, unnecessarily, pointlessly
돌다 = to spin, to turn around, to rotate
헤어지다 = to part, to break up
Why is my heart beating so quickly?
재밌다 = to be fun, to be interesting
in any case, no matter what
넘다 = to go over, to go beyond
Used when something unexpected happens abruptly.
at the end of the day, finally
Even if it hurts, hang on just a little bit more
똑같다 = to be exactly the same as
raise a dog [dog isn't on the list, whoops]
불편하다 = to be inconvenient, to be uncomfortable
Why did you stop all of a sudden?
It's because I look like my mom.
-ㄹ 뻔했다 = to just barely escape doing something, to have almost done something
You can hear (the sound of) the music, right?
비키다 = to move out of the way
벗다 = to take off, to undress
Often used as a way to say "shut up"
멋있다 = to be stylish, to be cool
I look forward to your kind cooperation.
We don't have a proper equivalent for this in English. Just start noticing the situations where they use the phrase.
the need disappeared (didn't need it anymore)
I'm so full; my stomach is bursting.
터지다 = to explode / to blow up
멋지다 = to be stylish, to be cool
No. I'm good enough on my own.
Our apartment is on the 7th floor.
층 = counter word for stories of a multistory building
뽑다 = to pull out, to pluck
착하다 = to be good-natured, to be good-hearted, kind
social awareness, wits, ability to read a room
Why did you deceive your mother?
속이다 = to fool, trick, lie to, deceive
I feel sorry for my dad.
Tell me in detail. / Tell me exactly what happened.
Give me one bottle of water, please.
The weather is really hot, isn't it?
to comfort someone, make them feel good
Something came up; I have something going on
He's being transferred to another hospital.
높다 = to be high (above the ground)
Your shoes need to be cleaned.
Literally: Wash your hands and (then) come (here).
a situation that has a strange, or no, explanation for its happening
잘생기다 = to be good looking, to be handsome
I can't breathe. I feel like I'm going to die.
상관없다 = to be of no concern
여전하다 = to remain, to be unchanged
Better than me. Better than me.
It's so obvious, who doesn't know?
티 = speck of dust, flaw, defect, trace
Literally: A  stain is showing... who wouldn't see it?
막히다 = to be stopped, to be blocked
I'll give you a ride home.
태우다 = to give someone a ride
The misunderstanding is resolved now, right?
풀리다 = to loosen, untie, release something bound
I can't drink coffee in the afternoon
It's a person that I cherish.
신기하다 = to be amazing or interesting
That's a bit of a problem
곤란하다 = to be troublesome, to be awkward
she flew like a bird in the sky
Bro! You're up! Are you alright?
a member of the bourgeois class
These are counted with Sino-Korean numbers, so 3 is pronounced 삼.
겁나다 = to be afraid, to be terrified
귀찮다 = to be a bother, to be annoying
to request, file, apply, turn in

This word is used to describe the first step in a process with many steps - the speaker is sort of unsure about whether or not they'll complete all the steps so this word is used to mean first when you're listing steps, but unsure about the rest. "First, let's just..."
on the way to grandma's house
This is a word that honors the person who lives there.
굉장하다 = to be marvelous, to be incredible
-성 = a suffix used to mean a quality
It's getting harder and harder and harder.
부끄럽다 = to be embarrassed, to be ashamed
I fell asleep for a moment
애쓰다 = to try, give it a shot, give it one's all
엄청나다 = to be massive, enormous, colossal, stupendous
It's more horrible than I thought.
끔찍하다 = to be gruesome, to be horrible
I had a lot of fun yesterday.
I was really happy at that time.
필요없다 = to be unnecessary; 필요 = a need; 없다 = to not exist
That barista wasn't here this morning.
Do you want to ruin your life?
It's so awkward. It's driving me crazy.
깔끔하다 = to be neat, to be tidy
자수하다 = to surrender, to turn oneself in
to do something that confuses other people
something that must be done / taken care of
넓다 = to be wide, to be spacious
섭섭하다 = to feel the lack of, to be disappointed
please accept an apology from me instead
Literally: Instead (of someone else), I will give you an apology.
